{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622147"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:00:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:00:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16788"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16788"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.27,0.27,0.33,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76648"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9479"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62145"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5245"},{"type":"tags","id":"9970"},{"type":"tags","id":"9988"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22454"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76648"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThalidomide analogues are an important class of medications used in modern cancer therapy, particularly for multiple myeloma. These compounds have evolved significantly from the original thalidomide molecule while maintaining certain therapeutic properties.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of thalidomide analogues?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hormone receptor antagonism","Immunomodulation and anti-angiogenesis","Direct cytotoxic effects","DNA synthesis inhibition","Anti-inflammatory activity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of thalidomide analogues involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmunomodulation and anti-angiogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E. These drugs modify the immune response by affecting T-cells and cytokine production, while also inhibiting new blood vessel formation in tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHormone receptor antagonism\u003C/strong\u003E - Thalidomide analogues do not act through hormone-mediated pathways\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect cytotoxic effects\u003C/strong\u003E - While these agents may have some direct anti-tumour activity, this is not their main mechanism of action\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDNA synthesis inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike traditional chemotherapy agents, thalidomide analogues do not directly interfere with DNA replication\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-inflammatory activity\u003C/strong\u003E - While these drugs have anti-inflammatory properties, their therapeutic benefit comes from a more complex combination of immunomodulatory and anti-angiogenic actions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EModern thalidomide analogues like lenalidomide and pomalidomide are particularly effective in multiple myeloma treatment through these dual mechanisms. They require careful monitoring and strict pregnancy prevention due to their teratogenic potential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thalidomide analogues like lenalidomide work through multiple mechanisms including immunomodulation and anti-angiogenic effects.","Thalidomide analogues are primarily used in the treatment of multiple myeloma and other haematological malignancies.","These medications require strict pregnancy prevention due to their teratogenic effects."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62145"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16788"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62145"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:12:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:12:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9479"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76648"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and re